### OWID Checklist for Testing Data 

1. Is there any data?

Yes and can be found [here](https://github.com/pcm-dpc/COVID-19) and [here](https://www.epicentro.iss.it/coronavirus/).

2. Do numbers refer to ‘performed tests’ or ‘individuals tested’?

In Italy "swabs" ("tamponi") refers to "performed tests" [github repo wiki](): the same person is tested multiple times (even 5/6 times [video]()). 

In particular patients who are recovered from COVID-19 are tested at least 3 times (1 positive and 2 negative)

NB: "Recovered" ("guariti") in the official data refers not only to those actually recovered (who tested negative twice), but to those who are discharged from hospital 
* https://www.ilpost.it/2020/04/02/guariti-coronavirus-protezione-civile/)
* https://www.sanita24.ilsole24ore.com/art/aziende-e-regioni/2020-04-02/coronavirus-cartabellotta-fondazione-gimbe-sovrastimato-numero-guariti-rischi-serve-chiarezza-orientare-scelte-103855.php?uuid=ADkV6eH 

3. Are negative results included? Are pending results included?

The total number of tests performed includes negative test results, but it  doesn't include the number of tests that are pending results [lombardy study early phase]().

4. Do the figures include all tests conducted in the country, or only some? 

Figures reported by Italy include all tests conducted in all working laboratories of the country. 
1. [Testing protocol, 27-02](http://www.trovanorme.salute.gov.it/norme/renderNormsanPdf?anno=2020&codLeg=73444&parte=1%20&serie=null)
1. [Testing protocol, 09-03](https://www.fnopi.it/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Circolare_9_marzo_2020.pdf)
1. [Testing protocol, 03-04](http://www.trovanorme.salute.gov.it/norme/renderNormsanPdf?anno=2020&codLeg=73799&parte=1%20&serie=null)

5. Are all regions and laboratories within a country submitting data on the same basis?

Yes, all Italian regions and labs submit testing data on the same basis (i.e. tests performed). [github repo]()

6. What period do the published figures refer to?

The figures published at a given date attempt to include all tests conducted up to that date, but significant and variable delays: both from symptom onset to lab confirmation (T_symptoms) and from from lab confirmation to official database update (T_lab) .
* [ISS](https://www.epicentro.iss.it/coronavirus/bollettino/Bollettino-sorveglianza-integrata-COVID-19_6-aprile-2020.pdf)

For example, in Lombardy T_symptoms = 7.3 days (1-20, 95% CI) and T_lab = 3.6 (1-10, 95% CI) https://arxiv.org/ftp/arxiv/papers/2003/2003.09320.pdf .

7. Are there any issues that affect the comparability of the data over time?

There have been significant hanges over time in the national testing protocol / recommendation.
* [ISS infographic](https://www.epicentro.iss.it/en/coronavirus/bollettino/Infografica_8aprile%20ENG.pdf)
1. [Testing protocol, 27-02](http://www.trovanorme.salute.gov.it/norme/renderNormsanPdf?anno=2020&codLeg=73444&parte=1%20&serie=null)
1. [Testing protocol, 09-03](https://www.fnopi.it/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Circolare_9_marzo_2020.pdf)
1. [Testing protocol, 03-04](http://www.trovanorme.salute.gov.it/norme/renderNormsanPdf?anno=2020&codLeg=73799&parte=1%20&serie=null)

8. What are the typical testing practices in the country?

Since not all Italian regions follow the protocol/recommendation of the central government there is significant regional heterogeneity in testing practices (e.g. see the completely different strategies of Veneto and Lombardia)

* [Perché non stiamo facendo più tamponi?](https://www.ilpost.it/2020/04/04/coronavirus-tamponi-test-problemi-numero/)
* [La differenza tra il numero di tamponi e il numero delle persone testate](https://www.ilpost.it/2020/03/26/coronavirus-tamponi-eseguiti-persone-testate/)
* [La Lombardia non fa tutti i tamponi che dovrebbe](https://www.ilpost.it/2020/03/27/tamponi-lombardia-fontana-coronavirus/)

Up to 20/03 we could identify 3 classes of testing practices described by the following pseudocode. ![image]

Consider two patients $A$ and $B$ living in the same house in the region $R \in \{X, Y, Z\}$ such that

* $A$ has no symptoms;
* $B$ suffers from symptoms compatible with **COVID-19**;
* $X$ respects the ministerial protocol dated 9-03 (e.g. Piedmont);
* $Y$ makes more tests than those recommended by the protocol dated 9-03 (e.g. Veneto)
* $Z$ makes fewer tests than those recommended by the protocol dated 9-03 (e.g. Lombardy). 

If $A$ and $B$ live in $X \Rightarrow$

1. ASL sends an ambulance team of health-workers who perform the test on him, but not to $A$ as he does not show any symptoms.
2. $A$ ends up in isolation, since in contact with a person who is definitely infected.

If $A$ and $B$ live in $Y \Rightarrow$

1. Test to $B$ 
2. Test to $A$ 
3. Test to the first and second neighbors (e.g. parents, friends, condominiums) in the hope of finding and isolating all the positives.

If $A$ and $B$ live in $Y \Rightarrow$

1. No test to $B$ (unless $B$ needs hospital care)
2. No test to $A$
3. No isolation from $A$ because there is no evidence that $B$ is positive despite its symptoms.



[Testing protocol, 09-03](https://www.fnopi.it/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Circolare_9_marzo_2020.pdf)

9. Might any of the information above be lost in translation?

The most important documents are translated in English by the official sources (ISS, PC, Ministero della Salute). Unfortunately there are multiple biases, missed daily data which have nothing to do with language translation or interpretation.


